  "output": "## Codebase profile\n\nThis is a Python async job-scraper (fetchers.py → filters.py → store.py → notify.py, orchestrated by pipeline.py), backed by SQLite, with a Claude-CLI wrapper in agent.py and prompt files under `modes/`. **There is no React/frontend code** — I've substituted the closest equivalent finding (redundant per-item recomputation) where the task asked about re-renders.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-73` (the big one)\n\n`Store.diff()` runs one `SELECT` per job, in a Python loop, for every job across every source on every run:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    new, changed = [], []\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    for job in jobs:\n        row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\",\n                          (job.key,)).fetchone()          # <-- 1 query per job\n        ...\n```\n\nMicrosoft/Amazon boards alone can be thousands of jobs (`max_pages=40` × 10/page). That's thousands of individual cursor round-trips plus individual `INSERT`/`UPDATE` statements per row, each auto-parsed/prepared by sqlite3.\n\n**Fix**: batch-load existing hashes once, diff in memory, then use `executemany` for writes:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's ~999 var limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        qmarks = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        existing.update(self.conn.execute(\n            f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({qmarks})\",\n            chunk).fetchall() and dict(self.conn.execute(\n            f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({qmarks})\", chunk)))\n\n    new, changed, unchanged_keys = [], [], []\n    to_insert, to_update = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job); to_insert.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif prev_hash != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); to_update.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append(job.key)\n\n    if to_insert:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,...,:now,:now)\"\"\", to_insert)\n    if to_update:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\"\"\", to_update)\n    if unchanged_keys:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                               [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round-trips into O(N/900) SELECTs + 3 `executemany` calls — the same shape as fixing an ORM N+1, just in raw SQL.\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job\n\n`filters.py:11-12` and `26,22`: `_compile()` is called from inside `match()`, which runs once per job:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    ...\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled every call\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)): # recompiled every call\n```\n\nFor N jobs this recompiles the same include/exclude keyword list N times each. **Fix**: compile once in `filter_jobs` and thread the compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re, ...)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None, ...):\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\nCheap fix, real win at thousands of jobs × several keywords.\n\n## 3. Redundant computation — `Job.to_row()` deep-copies `raw` just to discard it\n\n`models.py:71-75`:\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)      # deep-copies EVERY field, including `raw`\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)    # ...then throws the copy away\n```\n\n`dataclasses.asdict()` recursively deep-copies nested structures. `raw` holds the full unprocessed API payload per job (can be a sizeable dict, e.g. Greenhouse/Ashby postings with descriptions). Every insert/update deep-copies that payload only to delete it a line later — pure waste, and it happens for every job in the diff.\n\n**Fix**: build the row dict manually (also avoids `asdict`'s per-field overhead entirely):\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    return {\n        \"key\": self.key, \"source\": self.source, \"company\": self.company,\n        \"external_id\": self.external_id, \"title\": self.title, \"url\": self.url,\n        \"location\": self.location, \"department\": self.department,\n        \"employment_type\": self.employment_type, \"posted_at\": self.posted_at,\n        \"salary_range\": self.salary_range, \"content_hash\": self.content_hash,\n    }\n```\n\n## 4. Redundant computation — `content_hash` recomputed twice for changed rows\n\nIn `Store.diff`, `job.content_hash` (a `@property` running full SHA-256 over a joined string) is evaluated once for the comparison (`store.py:67`) and again inside `_update`'s call to `to_row()`. For a `slots=True` dataclass you can't use `functools.cached_property` directly, but you can compute it once and pass it through:\n\n```python\nh = job.content_hash\nif row is None:\n    new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now, h)\nelif row[\"content_hash\"] != h:\n    changed.append(job); self._update(cur, job, now, h)\n```\nand have `to_row(self, content_hash=None)` accept the precomputed value instead of recalling the property. Minor, but free once you're already touching this code for fix #1.\n\n## 5. Caching opportunity — Meta's scraped auth tokens\n\n`fetch_meta` (fetchers.py:537-574) re-fetches `https://www.metacareers.com/jobs` and re-scrapes `lsd`/`__spin_*` tokens on every single run, purely to get one POST authorized. That's an extra full-page fetch per run for a token that's valid for the life of that page session. If jobsquare ever moves to more frequent polling (the `6ae8083` commit added a 12h scheduled run), consider caching the token with a short TTL (e.g. 10 min) keyed in `Store.meta` (which already exists for the scan marker) to skip the page fetch when unexpired. Low priority at 12h cadence, worth it if cadence tightens.\n\n## 6. Pagination fetches are correctly sequential — not a bug, but note the cost\n\n`fetch_microsoft`/`fetch_netflix`/`fetch_amazon`/`fetch_google`/`fetch_twosigma`/`fetch_optiver` all page with `await` in a `for` loop (sequential, not concurrent) — this is *correct* here since each ATS session is stateful/rate-limit-sensitive and total concurrency is already bounded by the `Semaphore(concurrency)` in `fetch_all`. No change needed; flagging only so it's not mistaken for an oversight when reading the diff.\n\n## No memory leaks found\n\nThis is a run-once CLI (`cli.py` → `run_sync` → `asyncio.run`), not a long-lived server — the classes of leak that matter for servers (unclosed connections across requests, growing caches, dangling listeners) don't apply structurally. The one resource that matters, `httpx.AsyncClient`, is opened and closed with `try/finally` in `fetch_all` (fetchers.py:770-787) correctly, including on partial failure. `Store.conn` is closed via context manager in `pipeline.py:42` and `agent.py:54`. Nothing to fix here.\n\n## Priority order\n\n1. **`store.py` N+1 fix** — biggest real win, scales with total job count across all sources (thousands per run).\n2. **`filters.py` regex recompilation** — cheap, same N-scaling.\n3. **`models.py` `asdict` deep-copy** — cheap, removes wasted allocation on the hot path.\n4. Everything else is minor/optional.\n",
